Boil a large #pot{} of salted water for the @dried rigatoni{180%grams}.

When boiling, add the rigatoni to the @water{to taste} and bring back to the boil.

Cook until softened, ~{12%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and pop back in the pot.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to stop it sticking together.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Meanwhile, trim the @courgette{1}(trimmed and sliced into 1cm half-moons), halve lengthways.

Roughly chop the @parsley{5%grams}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Zest half the @lemon{1/2}(zested and cut into thick wedges).

Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a garlic press).

Place a large #pan{} over high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the courgette and cook until starting to brown, ~{3-4%minutes} on each side.

Add the garlic and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Once the courgettes are browned, reduce the heat.

Add the @creme fraiche{125%grams}, @water{50%ml} and @vegetable stock{1%sachet} to the pan.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} and stir to combine.

Bring to a simmer and cook until the sauce has thickened slightly, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir the @prawns{180%grams} into the sauce.

Continue to simmer until the prawns are cooked through, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Add a splash of water if the sauce is a bit thick.

Meanwhile, mix together the lemon zest and remaining parsley in a #small bowl{}.

Toss the drained rigatoni in the sauce.

Season to taste with a squeeze of lemon juice, salt and pepper.

Serve in bowls garnished with the lemon and parsley topping.